annotations: Butterfly guts on the windshield
Once again smashing the typical symbols of romanticism and love.
Great artists, narcissistic
The narrator is probably trying to be a great artist and is justifying the romantic aversion by saying that great artists are self-absorbed.
A cold heart and an altered state of mind
They are against traditional romance and appear very stoic and phlegmatic. They are probably drunk or high.
I’ve got affection to criticize, monogamy to abhor
Their disillusionment with romance leads to them to attack all of its typical facets. These lyrics play off of the irony of their namesake coming from romantic poet T.S. Eliot.

annotatable.link_title: Like How You Are by P.S. Eliot
annotatable.title: Like How You Are

annotations:
And I don’t really care about the future
 I care about what keeps you away

The narrator’s perception of time isn’t forward-oriented, but experience-oriented. For her, time is marked by the entrance and retreat of loved ones; by nostalgia and the possibility to create more nostalgia.

It’s an eternal conundrum, why we do what we do
 And we always discontinue what we don’t misconstrue

The narrator is bored by things that do not confuse her. She searches for people and situations that feel alternate and jarring. Here she realizes that both she and her partner have tried to make each other embody some enigmatic “other”,  only to realize the futility of such a search
